user_description:
On mobile go to your web browser like Chrome and type transgenderteensurvivalguide.tumblr.com/faq
 and please read the FAQ before you send us an ask!We are a blog created for people of all ages who have questions concerning their gender identity. Transgender is an umbrella term that is inclusive of, but not limited to (nor forced upon), trans women, trans men, non-binary people, genderfluid people, genderqueer people, agender people, multigender people, pre/post/non op people, and anyone who doesn't identify as the gender assigned to them at birth. This blog is designed to be a safe and supportive space where you are able to share your stories and concerns, as well as receive help and resources! As a disclaimer, none of us have a phD in Advice. Our responses come from a place of personal experience or mild research and you are in no way inclined to agree with or take everything that we say into consideration. However, we appreciate your support and hope that we help and make a difference in your life, as well as the lives around you! 
 Due to the volume of asks we receive, we cannot guarantee that all asks will be answered. We try to prioritize urgent and time-sensitive questions, but we cannot guarantee an answer even if it is marked as such. 
Thank you, and welcome to TTSG!

user_description: Go to your web browser like Chrome and type brownandtrans.tumblr.com/faq This is a blog where trans people of color can submit pictures of themselves! Anyone can follow! Thank you for your support :)
text:
I’ve found myself wondering “Where are the trans people of color?” a million times.
In my life, I’m often the only person of color in a room of trans people. I’ve noticed it is harder to find pictures and reviews of products (like packers) in the non-white skin tones. I see fewer pictures of POC post-surgery, and fewer people of color documenting their changes on HRT. Selfies of trans people, binary or non-binary, tend to skew towards the white and AFAB side. Hopefully, this blog can provide a sense of community and inclusion for all trans people of color. 
This blog is a place where we can answer that question. Where are the trans people of color? We’re right here! We’re talking about how our day went, about our families, about coming out, about our pets, about our transitions, about our ups and downs. We are here. We exist. This is a new blog for TPOC (trans people of color) to submit selfies of themselves! Anyone and everyone is allowed to follow us, all support is welcome, but only TPOC can send selfies.

user_title: i write sins not relatable content
user_description: m. / 26 / any pronouns
text:
if cis women can bulk up and wear baggy pants and crop their hair short and go without makeup or shaving their pits/legs/anywhere else, co-opt traditionally ‘masculine’ behaviors, and still be viewed as women–even praised for how very feminist they are in doing so–then so can trans women. that’s it. end of.
and if cis men who love fashion and florals and pink, and wear dresses and makeup and love to bake, can be comfortable in their masculinity and praised as revolutionary for doing so, then–you guessed it–so can trans men. that’s it. end of.
not one single person on earth has any right to dictate how anyone else pilots their respective flesh suits. not one single person on earth has any right to claim someone is ‘faking’ their gender or performing a gender incorrectly when gender is arbitrary as hell as-is.

user_description: Go to your web browser like Chrome and type brownandtrans.tumblr.com/faq This is a blog where trans people of color can submit pictures of themselves! Anyone can follow! Thank you for your support :)
text:
I’ve found myself wondering “Where are the trans people of color?” a million times.
In my life, I’m often the only person of color in a room of trans people. I’ve noticed it is harder to find pictures and reviews of products (like packers) in the non-white skin tones. I see fewer pictures of POC post-surgery, and fewer people of color documenting their changes on HRT. Selfies of trans people, binary or non-binary, tend to skew towards the white and AFAB side. Hopefully, this blog can provide a sense of community and inclusion for all trans people of color. 
This blog is a place where we can answer that question. Where are the trans people of color? We’re right here! We’re talking about how our day went, about our families, about coming out, about our pets, about our transitions, about our ups and downs. We are here. We exist. This is a new blog for TPOC (trans people of color) to submit selfies of themselves! Anyone and everyone is allowed to follow us, all support is welcome, but only TPOC can send selfies.

user_description: A blog focused on bigender, nonbinary, and trans stuff and bits of my personal experience as a (mostly) out bigender person. I'm chronically ill, so if my spoon meter has 1 spoon or I'm not posting, that's why I'm not answering asks, sorry
text:
You know what I want? A transgender store.
It has “traditional men’s,” “traditional women’s,” and “whatever” clothes sections. There are posters converting men’s and women’s clothing sizes. Each stack of clothing item has both sizing systems on it. They carry a wider range of sizes than usual, with lots of extra small clothes in the “traditional men’s” section and extra large/extra tall clothes in the “traditional women’s” section. They have shoes in all sizes. The dressing rooms are gender neutral. There are binders, gaffes, breast forms, and packers, with leaflets on how to use them. There’s a section with makeup and jewelry. The staff are friendly and knowledgeable. There’s a stack of handouts with transgender resources that people can take home for free. There are bookshelves with transgender books you can buy, as well as a small library. No one is gendered, and people can buy whatever they want without judgement.

user_description:
Feel free to ask us questions about being genderfluid, genderflux or non-binary, or submit something cute!
• Happy Asks! send us positive asks about your real life experiences! tagged with ‘happy’ 
••• About The Mods •••
I’m Glade and I'm a polyamorus panromantic demibisexual afab genderfluid, ce/ceir/ceirself pronouns! I am also a wiccan witch.
I'm Liv! I’m a girlflux, asexual lesbian. Pronouns she/her. (I can also answer questions about the ace/aro spectrum!)
I'm Rowan, a genderqueer nonbinary lesbian! They/them. [Rowan stopped being a mod on this blog, but we still contact them.]
I'm Maxine, I'm an AMAB demigirlflux lesbian from New Zealand. She/Her pronouns, or je/jem/jer if you feel fancy. 
••• please notice that we are all minors!

Gentle reminder that LGBT individuals in M/F presenting relationships still belong at pride. M/F relationships do not erase their LGBT identity.
They might be trans, they might be bi/pan, they might be closeted. 
Whatever their identity is, it’s none of your business.
Don’t judge, Stay safe, Spread love, Happy pride!
